Breaking within a string statement can be done by using a backslash '\' at the end of the first line.
Example:
document.write("This is \
a program");

If you change to a new line when not within a string statement, JavaScript ignores the break in the line.
Example:
var x=1, y=2,
z=x+y;

The above code is valid, though not advisable as it hampers debugging.

Global variables are available throughout the entire code and have no scope. The var keyword is used to declare a local variable or object. If the var keyword is omitted, a global variable is declared.

Example:
// Declare a global variable:
globalVariable = "Test";

The problems with global variables include name clashes between local and global scope, and difficulty in debugging and testing code that relies on global variables.

// for Single line comments

/*
