It can be done in the following ways:

document.getElementById("myText").style.fontSize = "20";

or

document.getElementById("myText").className = "anyclass";

Variable typing allows assigning different types of values to the same variable.

Example:
i = 10;
i = "string";

This is called variable typing.

The parseInt() function is used to convert numbers between different bases. parseInt() takes the string to be converted as its first parameter, and the second parameter is the base of the given string.

To convert 4F (base 16) to integer:
parseInt("4F", 16);

The delete keyword is used to delete a property and its value from an object.

Example:
var student = {age:20, batch:"ABC"};
delete student.age;

Escape characters (backslash \) are used when working with special characters like single quotes, double quotes, apostrophes, and ampersands. Place backslash before the characters to display them.

Example:
document.write("I am a \"good\" boy.");

The pop() method removes the last element from an array and returns that element. The array is altered.

Example:
var cloths = ["Shirt", "Pant", "TShirt"];
cloths.pop();
// Now cloths becomes ["Shirt", "Pant"]

Try… Catch… finally is used to handle exceptions in JavaScript.

```javascript
try {
    // Code
} catch(exp) {
    // Code to handle exception
} finally {
    // Code that runs regardless of success or failure
}
```

Variable typing allows assigning different types of values to the same variable.

Example:
i = 8;
i = "john";

Properties are assigned to objects in these ways:
obj["class"] = 12;

or

obj.class = 12;

Strict Mode adds certain compulsions to JavaScript, showing errors for code that might be problematic or unsafe. It helps JavaScript engines work more efficiently.

Strict mode can be enabled by adding "use strict" at the beginning of a file or function.

Example:
function myfunction() {
    "use strict";
    var v = "This is a strict mode function";
}

The status can be acquired as follows:
alert(document.getElementById('checkbox1').checked);

If the CheckBox is checked, this returns TRUE.

A closure is a function that has access to its outer function's variables even after the outer function has returned.

Example:
function greeter(name, age) {
    var message = name + " says howdy!! He is " + age + " years old";
    return function greet() {
        console.log(message);
    };
}

var JamesGreeter = greeter("James", 23);
JamesGreeter(); // Logs the message

The for-in loop is used to loop through the properties of an object.

Syntax:
for (variable in object) {
    // statement or block to execute
}

In each iteration, one property from the object is assigned to the variable.

An anonymous function is declared without a named identifier and is often inaccessible after declaration.

Declaration example:
var anon = function() {
    alert('I am anonymous');
};
anon();

.call() is used when the number of arguments is known, passing them individually.
.apply() is used when the number is unknown, passing arguments as an array.

Example:
someObject.myMethod.call(someOtherObject, '<', '>');
someObject.myMethod.apply(someOtherObject, ['<', '>']);

Properties are assigned to objects similarly to assigning values to variables.
Example:
Document.form.action="submit";

The unshift() method adds elements to the beginning of an array.

Example:
var name = ["john"];
name.unshift("charlie");
name.unshift("joseph", "Jane");
console.log(name);
// Output: ["joseph", "Jane", "charlie", "john"]

encodeURI() converts URL into hex coding.
decodeURI() converts encoded URL back to normal.

Example:
encodeURI("my test.asp?name=ståle&car=saab");
decodeURI("my%20test.asp?name=st%C3%A5le&car=saab");

Main loop types:
1. for loop
2. for/in loop
3. while loop
4. do…while loop

For loop syntax:
for(statement1; statement2; statement3) {
    // code to execute
}

While loop syntax:
while(condition) {
    // code to execute
}

Do-while syntax:
do {
    // code
} while (condition);

JavaScript supports object-oriented programming. Objects simulate real-life entities with properties and methods.

Creation:
var objName = new Object();
objName.property1 = value1;
objName.method1 = function() { /* code */ };

Or:
var objName = {property1: value1, method1: function() { /* code */ }};

Use for/in loop to iterate through object properties.

Syntax:
for (variable in object) {
    // code
}

Example:
var employee = {first:"John", last:"Doe", department:"Accounts"};
for (var x in employee) {
    console.log(x + ": " + employee[x]);
}

DOM methods:
- getElementById: Access by ID
- getElementsByTagName: Access by tag
- createElement: Create new element
- removeChild: Remove element

Event handling:
document.getElementById("btn").addEventListener("click", function() {
    alert("Clicked!");
});

Cookies store data on the user's computer. They're key/value pairs for remembering information like login details.

Create: document.cookie = "name=value; expires=date; path=/";
Read: var x = document.cookie;
Delete: Set expires to past date.

